{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"39670035-a0ec-4813-ab38-7dfa6a5e87aa","content":"\n\nIn your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Created\");\n    window.Activated     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Activated\");\n    window.Deactivated   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Deactivated\");\n    window.Stopped       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Stopped\");\n    window.Resumed       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Resumed\");\n    window.Destroying    += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Destroying\");\n    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Backgrounding\");\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Typical lifecycle flow:**\n\n| Transition | Events fired |\n|---|---|\n| App launch | `Created` → `Activated` |\n| User switches away | `Deactivated` → `Stopped` |\n| User returns | `Resumed` → `Activated` |\n| App closed | `Destroying` |\n| iOS/Mac background | `Backgrounding` (with `BackgroundingEventArgs.State` for state preservation) |\n\n> **Tip:** `Backgrounding` is iOS/macOS-only. On Android/Windows the equivalent path is `Stopped`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"531dbd34-97e7-4cfa-ade7-052001ceea3c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI Window lifecycle events and how to subscribe to them for logging/debugging. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI — I can answer directly without needing to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":430},"id":"1a97f04b-3a97-4b1a-a374-e59455998ead","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:47:43.330Z","parentId":"483e4ad8-407e-4a37-9f0d-8e974fdcc76d"}
